I think your presentation is terrific. The only reason I bothered with alterations is that I'm such a poor liar I'm liable to get the lies mixed up. So send it the way you have it if you wish.
All I have in income is my Social Security. Out of that I have to save enough for fare to the States twice a year. Only allowed to live here six months on a tourist permit. And of course living in New York is outrageous. So the closer together you can make the meetings with the producer the cheaper it will be for me.
Sent you an outline and an article for your magazine. Must have been a month ago. Did you get them?
Thanks a Million for all your effort.
Yours for a Better World
Slim
Slim Brundage
P.S. Will stop this A.M. and look at {am} Heritage. Just got yours yesterday.
Completed

Aug 26 - 71
Slim:
Gary tried to call you but could not reach you so - hope this will find you. Clark was not sick very long. - he passed away same night we took him to the hospital. Massive heart attach. Sure do miss him. I always hoped I would go first - but this we cannot control. I guess. Hope all is well with you. Got your address from Nancy Mitchell.
Heard from Dorothy & Roscoe but not ken. Lou passed away March 16-1971- She had emphysema & cancer of the throat.
Kay
Completed

There are birch trees on the hill, slight pretty things, some grow slowly like great oak trees. It is not for them to decide what will be, or how they will grow or when the seed will take or when they will wither and die. In life we have many burdens to bear, but that is not one of them. We do not know who will be born today, or who will die tomorrow. When a man's hour has come, he will go. You cannot stop a falling sparrow and neither can you take aim and hit one unless its hour has already come.
By Kay Brundage

Oct. 17-1971
Dear Slim,
Thank you for your letter and I too am looking forward to that "happy lonesome feeling". It isn't here as yet.
The Brundages do grow on you - you know. Have not heard a word from Delbert or ken.
Dorothy & Roscoe are in Carson but mostly Reno with their son & family.
Our fall season is here. We enjoyed a beautiful rain yesterday & last night. Today is sunny & clear.
If I am in town when you come in December - I will try to see you - Hope you are
Completed

still feeling like a top.
Louis' daughter & husband moved to Redway, Calif. They want me to move up there some time in the spring. I would like to. They are about 68 miles from Eureka, on the coast. Both of them will be looking for work. He wants to start his own business in art advertising. He is very good at it & will have help from his former boss. They have a lovely place in the Redwoods. A small town & oh, so beautiful. She has sort of adopted me as a mother, which makes me feel wanted too.

Gary & family are fine and have helped me so much.
I am trying to sell a rental near here, but so far not much response. Money is difficult to get for buyers these days. But I am hoping it will go soon. Then my home here. so on & on it goes. One day after another.
How is your book coming along?
Love
Kay.

659 Wellington Chicago Ill  June 26, 1965
Slim - Just finished reading and trying to group the poetry for the book-to-be.  We are in trouble - almost nothing usable in the “light and fluffy” category, either in doggerel or in regular verse.  Two possibilities to remedy this - 1) you can look for another envelope; 2) They didn’t turn ‘em in, and need some reminding (The reason they aren’t usable is they aren’t good enough.). Or, we can try with what we have and forget our preconceived section and other notions, if you’d like to get it moving now.  In this event, let me know which evening you’ll have a free hour and we can go over what we have “in the bag” and can decide what to do with it.  Will pop over Thursday night, anyway to pick up the missing ones.  But we do need more couplets, quatrains, and verse up to 4 stanzas in length.  On another topic, do you have any use for the dope I gathered on Prohibition and the propaganda and facts from the liquor groups? (more)

Am convinced that you're right in thinking the Luckiest Man Alive will need an overhaul before it is published. But I'm with your Joan. If a third draft will get them to accept it, provided you make the changes that they want, then it's well worth doing. Let me know what Paul Romaine says - I'll keep my fingers crossed. We'll really have a celebration when you get a book published. I'll invite the whole world and serve sunflower seeds and Manhattans. 
That program on the Paris Peace Conference sounds delightful. Let me know what StanDale says.
Presume you're gears are now changed for the windy city, and that you'll have a lovely summer just as soon as you can get the accomodations bit straightened out. Sure wish you well on this. And don't worry about me, doll; it's just the kind of thing I have to ride out. Take care. 
Luv 'n a hug, 
Esther
P.S. Did my letter to Guadalajara ever catch up with you?
Completed

10/10/72. HAPPY COLUMBUS DAY across the top margin. Dear Slim, Since Thursday is the day that Columbus was supposed to have discovered America, but by legislation, we celebrated it yesterday, and since Columbus never did discover America anyway, I thought  it fitting to write and send you my very best wishes for a happy Columbus Day. Hope you didn't have to go to the bank and find it closed, or that some important mail failed to arrive because of a postman's holiday, and that the day treated you all right otherwise. On this end, everything is quiet at work before the storm. I am waiting to be called
Completed

on a "crash" proposal being bid in an effort to get the Navy to award McDonnell Douglas nearly $1 billion dollars worth of work. It's a nice piece of change, but to me it represents no more than about 2 or 3 weeks of working long hours 7 days a week, without benefit of extra pay. I just hope I can get the plague off both mine houses and escape from the joint. In an effort to do so, I raised the number of points I would pay for a buyer to 4 1/2 N.B.: 4 and one half, which means he would get his money on a GI loan for 1 1/2NB., 1 and one half% with no money down. And so far, the response has been a heavy silence. That's on Inglewood. As for the beach house, I'm afraid it will take years. Through no fault of mine,
Completed

the title got clouded and my lawyer is making noises necessary as a preliminary to suing to clear up the title. I can just picture waiting in line for the court for years! Grr! On a happier front, weight control unclear out over compulsive eating and I'm now having the buttons on the falda reset to where your girl had them in the first place. Am also going to try out a gym to get rid of some unwelcome girth. Perhaps by the time you get here, I'll be my skinny, energetic sylph again. Nuff of this nonsense. Am reading Schlessinger's "The Roosevelt Years," "The Greening
Completed

of America," and still trying to finish John Barth's "Giles Goat Boy." But every time I pick up "Goat Boy," I keep turning to the play within the play where he finds out his wife is his momma and break up in laughter. And that shoots Barth for the night. And how's by you? Luv, Ester
